17. Key Takeaways
============================================================

1. Depth map should not necessarily be coded like ordinary texture video.
2. VVC LD/RA inter tools may not be optimal for depth maps, especially when inter syntax overhead is large.
3. Block-wise plane representation is a more geometry-aware way to code depth.
4. Inverse-depth plane is more compatible with perspective camera geometry than linear-depth plane.
5. Camera parameter can transform previous reconstructed plane into a current-view predictor.
6. Good camera-aware plane candidates can reduce bits through copy or small delta modes.
7. Projection PSNR is essential, because depth PSNR alone does not fully measure usefulness for view prediction.
8. Backward projection with reconstructed depth is the key evaluation method for checking whether coded depth is useful for texture prediction.
9. Translation/parallax scenes are the most promising cases for depth-camera predictors.
10. Pure rotation is less favorable for depth map coding because rotation can often be handled by homography-like predictors without depth.


