18. Short Abstract for PPT
============================================================

We investigate a geometry-aware depth map compression framework for video coding. Instead of coding depth maps as ordinary texture frames, each block is represented by an inverse-depth plane. The encoder selects among direct coding, copy mode, and delta mode using RD optimization. Candidate planes are generated from spatial neighbors, temporal same-position blocks, and camera-parameter-based plane warping from previous reconstructed depth. Since perspective projection maps 3D planes to affine inverse-depth surfaces, inverse-depth plane coding is better aligned with camera geometry than linear-depth plane coding. To evaluate the practical value of reconstructed depth, we use it for backward projection of a previous GT video frame into the current view and measure projection PSNR. This evaluates whether the compressed depth map remains useful for view prediction, not only whether the depth map itself has high PSNR.


============================================================
19. One-Slide Summary
============================================================

Problem:
- Depth maps require extra bits.
- Standard VVC inter coding may be inefficient for depth maps.
- Depth PSNR alone does not guarantee good view prediction.

Proposed direction:
- Represent depth blocks as inverse-depth planes.
- Use copy/delta modes with predictor candidates.
- Generate a camera-aware plane predictor from previous reconstructed depth and camera parameters.

Main geometry:
- 3D plane under perspective projection is affine in inverse depth.
- Plane transform:
    plane_cur = inverse(W2C_cur * C2W_prev).T * plane_prev
- Reconstructed depth is evaluated by backward projection:
    GT(t-1) + recon depth(t) + cameras → prediction(t)

Evaluation:
- Measure depth bits, depth PSNR, projection PSNR, valid-region PSNR, candidate selection ratios.

Expected benefit:
- Strongest in translation/parallax scenes.
- Less effective in pure rotation or very small motion.
